===Etymology===
From {{etyl|fro}} {{term|moneie}} (French: {{term|monnaie}}). Derived from the {{etyl|la}} {{term|moneta}}; after Rome's temple, Juno Moneta, where coin was minted.

===Noun===
{{wikipedia}}
{{en-noun|''normally [[uncountable]], but '''[[moneys]]''' or '''[[monies]]'''}}

''A legally or socially binding conceptual contract of entitlement to wealth, void of intrinsic value, payable for all debts and taxes, and regulated in supply.''


*'''Legally or socially binding:''' due to law or social acceptance.<ref name=Aristotale350BCE>Aristotle 350 B.C.E., book 5</ref>
*'''Conceptual:''' because it does not exist in the natural world.<ref name=Aristotale350BCE>Aristotle 350 B.C.E., book 5</ref>
*'''Contract of entitlement to wealth:''' not be confused with [[wealth]].
*: Example: if money becomes worthless within a society, it does not destroy wealth ''(i.e. books, houses, land, products)''.
:Also, entitlement implies ownership ''without obligation'' whereas [[credit]] ''implies obligation'', therefore money and credit are distinct.<ref name=Montesquieu1752>Montesquieu 1752, section 17</ref>
*'''Void of intrinsic value:''' being an abstraction of the law it is not to be confused with a commodity. Example: when speculators treat money like a commodity, it stops functioning as a pledge for wealth and hence as money.<ref name=AlexanderDelMar1885>Del Mar 1885</ref>
*'''Payable for all debts and taxes:''' for instance, if a government refuses to accept something as payment for taxes, it no longer functions as money.<ref name=Zarlenga2002>Zarlenga 2002</ref>
*'''Regulated in supply:''' to prevent problems with inflation or deflation.<ref name=Zarlenga2002>Zarlenga 2002</ref>


==== Popular usage ====
* Hard [[cash]] in the form of [[banknote]]s and [[coin]]s, as opposed to cheques/checks. [[credit card]]s, or [[credit]] more generally.
*The total value of [[liquid asset]]s available for an individual or other economic unit, such as cash and bank deposits.
*[[wealth|Riches]]; valuable material possessions. ''(He was born with '''money'''.)''
*A person who funds an operation.
* {{context|as a modifier}} Of or pertaining to '''money'''; [[monetary]]. ''('''money''' supply, '''money''' market)''


